If removing all the diseased leaves will leave your plant completely bare, consider using a pesticide/fungicide spray. This won't cure the disease but it will stop it spreading. Always follow the instructions on the spray container carefully. Hold the bottle about 30 centimeter (11.8 in) away from the plant and spray enough to coat the leaf but not enough to cause any drips. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a8/Deal-with-Mildew-Leaf-Disease-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Deal-with-Mildew-Leaf-Disease-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a8/Deal-with-Mildew-Leaf-Disease-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Deal-with-Mildew-Leaf-Disease-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Treat the plant either early, or late in the day, so you don't spray pollen-spreading insects like bees. Wait 14 days and then repeat. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d8/Deal-with-Mildew-Leaf-Disease-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Deal-with-Mildew-Leaf-Disease-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d8/Deal-with-Mildew-Leaf-Disease-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Deal-with-Mildew-Leaf-Disease-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
